lme, Devon, England":"Uffculme, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1255–":"1255–Afdød","1255–Female":"1255–Afdød","1254–Male":"1254–Afdød","1278–Male":"1278–Afdød","1296–Male":"1296–Afdød","1306–Female":"1306–Afdød","1319–Male":"1319–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1384–Male":"1384–Afdød","1232–1346":"1232–1346","1236–Female":"1236–Afdød","about 1319":"omkring 1319","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1254":"1254","1296":"1296","1384":"1384","       1306":"1306","1319":"1319","1306":"1306","Bradfield, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Lusterhill,, Wilts., England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Uffculme, Devon, England":"Uffculme, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1255–":"1255–Overleden","1255–Female":"1255–Overleden","1254–Male":"1254–Overleden","1278–Male":"1278–Overleden","1296–Male":"1296–Overleden","1306–Female":"1306–Overleden","1319–Male":"1319–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1384–Male":"1384–Overleden","1232–1346":"1232–1346","1236–Female":"1236–Overleden","about 1319":"circa 1319","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1254":"1254","1296":"1296","1384":"1384","       1306":"1306","1319":"1319","1306":"1306","Bradfield, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Lusterhill,, Wilts., England":"Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Uffculme, Devon, England":"Uffculme, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1255–":"1255–Deceased","1255–Female":"1255–Deceased","1254–Male":"1254–Deceased","1278–Male":"1278–Deceased","1296–Male":"1296–Deceased","1306–Female":"1306–Deceased","1319–Male":"1319–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1384–Male":"1384–Deceased","1232–1346":"1232–1346","1236–Female":"1236–Deceased","about 1319":"about 1319","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1254":"1254","1296":"1296","1384":"1384","       1306":"1306","1319":"1319","1306":"1306","Bradfield, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Lusterhill,, Wilts., England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Uffculme, Devon, England":"Uffculme, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stowford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Stockport (Cheshire), which is recorded as  <i>Stokeport</i> in 1188,  <i>Stockford</i> in 1283–8,  <i>Stopford</i> in 1347,  <i>Stoppord</i> in 1337, and  <i>Stapporte</i> in 1583."],"variants":[{"name":"Stockforth","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."]},{"name":"Stopper","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Matthias.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone with a heavy stride or an awkward way of walking, from a conjectural Middle English word <i>stauper</i>, <i>stouper</i> or, with substitution of the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i>, Middle English <i>staupard</i>, <i>stoupard</i>.","English: perhaps an occupational name for a maker of stoups, from Middle English <i>staupe</i>, <i>stoupe</i>, <i>stope</i> (Old Norse <i>staup</i>, reinforced by Middle Dutch <i>stoop</i>), ‘jug, often made of leather; measure for liquids; vessel or container for holy water’. Alternatively, the name may derive from an unrecorded Middle English <i>stopper</i>, perhaps ‘maker of pails, buckets, or jugs’, a derivative of Middle English <i>stoppe</i> (Old English <i>stoppa</i>)."]},{"name":"Stockport","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."]},{"name":"Stobbart","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Stubard</i>,  <i>Stobard</i>, late Old English * <i>Stubheard</i>, recorded only in E Anglia, so the surname in post-medieval NE England may be due to migration from there via the east coast trade route. The post-medieval surname may have been confused with   Stappard   and   Stopford  , and in E Anglia it may have been absorbed into   Stibbard  ."]},{"name":"Stopard","meanings":["English:  see  Stoppard  ."]},{"name":"Stopforth","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."]},{"name":"Stoppard","meanings":["English: (i)  see  Stopford  . (ii)  see  Stappard  ."]},{"name":"Stappard","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, perhaps for someone with a heavy stride or an awkward way of walking, from a conjectural Middle English word * <i>stauper</i>, * <i>stouper</i> or, with substitution of the pejorative suffix  <i>-ard</i>, Middle English * <i>staupard</i>, * <i>stoupard</i>. Compare 19th-century Whitby (NR Yorks) dialect  <i>stauper</i> ‘a clumsy fellow, a clown’, from the dialect verb  <i>staup</i>,  <i>stowp</i>,  <i>stoop</i> ‘to walk clumsily and heavily’, which is recorded in   English Dialect Dictionary   from Northumb and Cumb southwards as far as Derbys and Lincs. The name was sometimes confused with   Stobbart   and perhaps with   Stopford  . (ii) occupational name, perhaps for a maker of stoups. * <i>Stauper</i>, * <i>Stouper</i>, and * <i>Stoper</i> would be unrecorded derivatives of Middle English * <i>staupe</i>,  <i>stoupe</i>,  <i>stope</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>staup</i>, reinforced by Middle Dutch  <i>stoop</i>), ‘a jug, often made of leather; a measure for liquids; a vessel or container for holy water’. This explanation accounts for the variation between  <i>Stauper</i>,  <i>Stoper</i>,  <i>Stooper</i>, and possibly  <i>Stopper</i>, but not the forms with final  <i>-d</i>,  <i>-t</i> or  <i>-th</i>, unless through false association with other names, such as (1) above."]},{"name":"Stockford","meanings":["English (Oxfordshire): in northern England and the North Midlands, usually a variant of <i>Stockport</i>, a habitational name from Stockport (Cheshire), from Old English <i>stoc</i> ‘place, secondary settlement’ + <i>port</i> ‘town, market’; elsewhere it may have a different origin, such as Stokeford in East Stoke (Dorset), which takes its name from East Stoke + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, meaning ‘the ford near (East) Stoke’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Stowford was born in 1255, in England, United Kingdom, her father, John Stofford, was 23 and her mother, Mrs. John Stofford, was 20. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with John Ford Walrond. She died in Uffculme, Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1255–":"1255–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1254–Male":"1254–Surnud","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1384–Male":"1384–Surnud","1232–1346":"1232–1346","1236–Female":"1236–Surnud","about 1319":"umbes 1319","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1254":"1254","1296":"1296","1384":"1384","       1306":"1306","1319":"1319","1306":"1306","Bradfield, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Lusterhill,, Wilts., England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Uffculme, Devon, England":"Uffculme, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1255–":"1255–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1254–Male":"1254–Kuollut","1278–Male":"1278–Kuollut","1296–Male":"1296–Kuollut","1306–Female":"1306–Kuollut","1319–Male":"1319–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1384–Male":"1384–Kuollut","1232–1346":"1232–1346","1236–Female":"1236–Kuollut","about 1319":"noin 1319","1236":"1236","1346":"1346","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1254":"1254","1296":"1296","1384":"1384","       1306":"1306","1319":"1319","1306":"1306","Bradfield, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bradfield, Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England","Lusterhill,, Wilts., England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Uffculme, Devon, England":"Uffculme, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Engla